    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Transportation"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The best way to reach Andorra is by car. If you’re traveling through France or heading to Spain, be sure to stop here. When arriving from France, you have two route options: a paid tunnel that runs flat or a mountain pass that takes about 15-20 minutes with sharp curves. Once you crest the 2400 meters high summit, you’ll face a steep descent. This mountain road is free, and offers beautiful views."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "However, a minor disadvantage of traveling by car in Andorra is the paid parking in larger towns. The system is well-organized, but free parking is not available. Outside the cities and in the mountains, though, parking is not a problem."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "If you’re in Andorra without a car, there is the option to use local buses for transportation."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Prices"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Andorra is significantly cheaper than neighboring France. A liter of gasoline can be up to 50 cents cheaper, so definitely wait until you reach Andorra to fill up your tank. The price of food in restaurants is also half of what it costs in France. Upon arrival, you’ll notice crowded gas stations and many stores that resemble duty-free shops at airports. Especially on weekends, it can be more difficult to enter Andorra, as many French families come here for cheap shopping, cheaper gas, and alcohol, which is less expensive than in the Czech Republic. Long traffic jams can form as a result. There’s only one road leading into Andorra from France, so you can’t avoid the queues, and you’ll have to slowly move up the mountain."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Places to Visit"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Cities"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The main attraction is the mountains, but the capital"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Andorra la Vella",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/C5RT6RuQNZXmxJm38",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "is also worth visiting, where you can expect a bit of chaos and paid parking (only the first 30 minutes are free). You can also visit the nearby town of"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Les Escaldes",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/X2H9JtSjyLv19ZBp7",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ", famous for its thermal springs and an aquapark. There are also beautiful mountain villages with traditional architecture and small churches, such as"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Canillo",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/vbKm9wb8JYWByLaf6",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "or"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "La Cortinada",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/UsGGFTxUqFSqAqRRA",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "."
        }
      ]
    },
