    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 3,
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Mountains"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "A beautiful yet challenging hike is to the highest peak in Andorra –"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Pic de Coma Pedrosa",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/U8DLBsQqGw7ssDx97"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "2946 m above sea level",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ". The starting point is"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Arinsal",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/qJxqGAUHwu2bpRkX9",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ". The route to the top is about 8 km long with an elevation gain of over 1500m. The trail is demanding and time-consuming, so make sure to allocate plenty of time. It is best to start early in the morning. If you make it to the base of the summit, you’ll be rewarded with a beautifully clear mountain lake. From there, a final steep climb awaits you. The last kilometer may seem endless, and some people even turn back at this point. But that’s a shame! At the summit, you’ll have a unique view of the Pyrenees peaks stretching as far as the eye can see. You can even spot the highest snowy peak of the mountain range – Pico de Aneto (3404m above sea level)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "It is theoretically possible to return via another route, which is about 2 km shorter. The elevation gain on this route is the same, making it very steep. The best option is to return the same way. The trail is well-marked, and no special equipment is required. If you’re not up for the full hike, it’s possible to split the route into two days. There are camping sites along the way or you can stay in a mountain hut for a fee."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Another beautiful and popular destination is the three lakes"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Tristaina (Estany de Més Amunt, del Mig, Primer)",
          "url": "https://goo.gl/maps/QEAZauRiyZJUSGyD8",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ". You can reach them by car to a high elevation (2200m above sea level) via the only road from El Serrat and then hike to the lakes (2400m above sea level). The hike is not difficult, but if you’re looking for more physical activity, you can hike up to the border peak"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Pic de Tristaina (2878m above sea level)",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ". The ascent is short but very steep, almost like a climbing route, though you won’t need any special equipment."
        }
      ]
    },
